##Skycity Lu Wei: Why said the film and Television Industry is experiencing an unprecedented reshuffle?

Micro-signal, Rancaijing

A feature presentation, a daily in depth report, redefines the innovation economy.

Original by ran CAIJING

By Yan Lijiao

Editor | Zhou Changfan

Into March, many industries began to resume work, "Film and Television Industry when can resume work" is still affecting many people.

In the epidemic continued to spread over 50 days, the film and television industry has been unprecedented impact. New Year's Eve film collective announced the withdrawal of stalls, the loss of the theater line. To save themselves, some theaters have to rely on "sideline" to ease the pressure on cash flow. A few days ago, Ali Film United Hungry, on-line "cinema delivery services. ". Movie theaters stocked up on popcorn, potato chips, coke and other snacks and eventually had to rely on online channels to clean up their inventory.

On February 23, the China Film Distribution and Exhibition Association issued a working proposal on the preparations for the resumption of work in cinemas, putting forward some specific proposals for the resumption of work in cinemas. But when the proposal was published, it was met with scepticism and was subsequently government of Beijing.

Although some cinemas have started to resume work in China, there is no clear timetable for when they will be fully open. Even if the theater opens normally, the producer may not choose to release at this time. The Global Film and Television Industry has been affected this time, with the release of James Bond: no time to die, scheduled for April 10 in North America, recently announced that it will be delayed until November 25. Even if there were a movie to watch, the audience would not necessarily walk into the theater at this time. The impact of the epidemic, almost transmitted to the film and television industry in every link.

Film and television industry has been a huge impact, but do not deny that the film and television industry itself exposed a lot of problems. China lacks the business models of Netflix, Amazon Studio, Hulu, Disney + , and continues its traditional cinema model. On the one hand, everyone in the industry is in danger, on the other hand, the difficult situation of the industry is forcing the two years lack of disruptive changes in the film and television industry to seek a new way out.

On March 5, joy media announced that the group had begun a strategic partnership with bytedance to arrange for theatrical films to be shown on bytedance's platforms, including but not limited to watermelon videos and Toutiao. Meanwhile, the group's "happy Premiere" APP has more than two million paying users.

Skycity founder Lu Wei believes the series of strategic collaborations between mom and bytedance is just a turning point, and the industry should take the opportunity to make more changes. Sky City, which has produced such films as the return of the great sage, Mount Kailash and the Himalayas, is considered a dark horse in the film industry.

Lu Wei analysis, around 2015, the film and Television Industry has done a lot of online and offline integration exploration. But there has been little innovation in business models since 2017. It's the lack of innovation that makes it so difficult to deal with an epidemic. The beginning of the 2020 epidemic completely reshuffled the film and Television Industry, "the majority of fans left the field, most of the rest are doers. "

From Netflix and Disney's development path, the future of film online will become the trend. China now has more than 40 theaters, more than 10,000 theaters, nearly 70,000 screens, theaters under the pounding will also be a new integration and business model changes.

Why would the film and television industry be hit so hard? What business models will emerge from cinema in the future? Will the on-line and off-line convergence from mom be the trend after all? Ran CAIJING had an in-depth dialogue with Lu Wei.

Here's what he said:

China needs Netflix and Disney models

Why the film and Television Industry will be so tested?

China's mobile Internet has grown especially fast in recent years, but it is not innovative enough and has too little insight into the model of entertainment products, including content and operating models. Before 2017, there are a lot of places where tradition meets the Internet. After 2017, there are few exciting explorations to be seen, especially in the last two years, when the entertainment industry has been very conservative.

Disney and Netflix offer good business models. Disney last year saw seven films that grossed more than $1 billion at the box office. Netflix raised its monthly fee, but it didn't lose users, and it made a profit. This shows that today's consumers, especially the post-00,90, they have been very accustomed to paying for content, and willing to pay more for their favorite content.

In addition to Netflix's eye-popping books like love, death and the robot, and Martin Scorsese's the Irishman, you'll find it's no longer an online content, its films are already cinema-like, big-screen, and no longer online versions of TV content in the usual sense. China has been slow to innovate in film distribution and screening in the past two or three years, and continues its traditional cinema model.

Pexels

The epidemic has exposed a lot of problems in the film and Television Industry, offline by a fundamental impact, offline and online integration is very weak.

The outbreak has hit content companies hard, especially those that have been trying to industrialize their movies and TV shows over the past decade. For the light on the short video, network big, short drama producers instead of good. But there is a problem, for small and medium content production companies, because capital capacity is limited, and the content production model is mostly traditional model. Right now, web content producers and theater content producers don't seem to be in the same league. The downstream of the web content producer is the platform, and the downstream of the theater content producer is the audience. It is a strange phenomenon that the content of the net is more 2C than the content of the film.

Then again, we shouldn't care about the form of entertainment, we should care about how it serves its users. What users need should be expanded within a reasonable framework, and practitioners should and need to be aware of new changes in the world.

The global impact on the offline entertainment industry has also been significant, with China being one of the most important markets for Hollywood overseas, and a slew of new films due out in February, including James Bond: no time to die and Mulan, have been delayed. Although Beijing and Shanghai have recently adopted some encouraging policies for cinemas, people are scared of the epidemic and are still very resistant to going out or gathering. So no matter how the policy support, offline entertainment is difficult to restore normal in the short term.

Mom provides the inflection point

It's time to play the game

I think it's a great example of how mom chose to work with Toutiao. I said to my friends that the film had a particularly good CEO who, in a very short period of time, had moved it online in a way that was now generally acceptable to internet users.

In this case, I talked to some theater investors, and they were frustrated, but they also felt that "movie online" was a trend, and some theater investors were already investing in or focusing on a new generation of VR theaters.

Since about 2014, Netflix has been at loggerheads with major film festivals, and many people don't think of Netflix as a film. Some European traditions hold that films must be shown in cinemas, where the mood of the scenes and the ritual of the group viewing are important. Our film culture has been interrupted for many years. Our understanding of the word "film" is different from that of European filmmakers or some old filmmakers. What can be shown in the cinema is called "film" . On the "film temperament" and "film sense" understanding, my attitude is conservative. Movies can continue to innovate, but the "feel of the movie" can't be cheap.

Movies are becoming more and more personal these days, especially with the popularity of VR goggles. Although I went to the movies every week, dozens, even hundreds, of them a year before the epidemic. But I can watch dozens or hundreds of movies a year with my VR glasses. Watching a movie in a Vr headset is another immersive, more active experience.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
For the current audience, there's no saying who's good and WHO's bad, and you need that kind of content in that scene, and it's great that someone has provided it to you. You will find that movie audiences are becoming more and more active, instead of passive consumption.

On the other hand, the supply of off-line movies is very small. There are only a handful of movies released in theaters each year, and even with more than 1,000 a year, it's remarkable that only five hundred of them have been approved for release in theaters. Really have a certain box office and word-of-mouth, can be seen by everyone is also one or two hundred. In fact, the off-line channel is far from meeting the needs of the movie audience.

No matter how the market, we must stand in the perspective of the development of the Times, this is one of them. Second, the outbreak and the case of lost mom are sure to make more people think again. 2015 is the climax of the cinema line construction, but also from the production side, the distribution side, the investment side to the audience feedback all shows a positive state of the period. But since 2017, the film industry has seen fewer spectacular cases, and may be in a period of adjustment.

From a business point of view, the Toutiao case is very high dimensional. Toutiao spent only a few hundred million dollars in the window to get what others could with ten billion or one billion. A lot of business, it's at a certain point in time, the headlines are very accurate.

But if Toutiao is like any other video platform, just to complement the Long Video Short Board, I don't see much commercial value. If it wasn't for the model, it was just a piece of the puzzle, and from an industry perspective, there wasn't much business imagination. There is no shortage of players on the market, and there will be no reward for one more.

I have also been watching the wechat video number recently, and my view is somewhat conservative. Wechat has become the tool that everyone has been using, because there is not so much interference. The video is time consuming, and users are using Wechat, not expecting it to provide him with more and more content. Its product value orientation, from the beginning should not be a content aggregation platform.

In the film and Television Industry, users need content support, not platform support, not flow support. Users will never be loyal to any platform, they will only be loyal to their own values, worldview. The only thing that can hold these things is the content itself.

The case of Mama Jiong has its uniqueness and its fortuity. Whether for the platform or content side, the best model should be the bottom line, not a one-time buyout. I'm not comfortable with the buy-out model, which creates a inertia in the creative side of the content team. Compared with Netflix and Disney + , there is still a lot of room for quality and commercial development. Moreover, China does not yet have a mature copyright-sharing mechanism.

Overall, the partnership is a kind of experiment, and will make more people reflect, which is a good thing. The market can't stay there forever. There's no movement.

Theaters shouldn't give up

Establish your own membership

From the development of Disney + , online and offline content integration, online screening must be the trend. Today's information age is no longer the original industrial age, in this era to continue the old rules, it is difficult to move into the future.

Around 2013, we were talking about the future of China's film distribution market, which is related to the Internet's focus on consumption and respect for content supply. But seven or eight years later, the line of distribution has not landed. Practitioners are still more focused on short-term business interests, on-the-spot profit returns, and various data indicators. It's a shame that we've wasted window of opportunity again and again to build user habits. Sometimes we have to look not just at the business, but at the model over time to see which option is really valuable to us. At this point, I'd like to put it another way, that the Internet has helped the cinema and in some ways destroyed something of value.

Before 2015, I had several cinema memberships, each offering a slightly different service. Later, online ticketing essentially destroyed the cinema's membership system. With no members, it's hard to get the service right. Online ticketing is a huge value transformation, but from the point of view of the fine operation of the theater, the theater is actually the advantage of the show destroyed the foundation. It's not too late. Theaters should have their own membership. The concept of private domain traffic is not different from the current concept of private domain traffic, which uses membership data, analyzes user types, provides them with better products and services, and displays differentiated brands to keep users consuming.

In the future, to do sub-line distribution, focus distribution, if there is no accurate understanding of user data and long-term tracking, it is not possible. Otherwise, decisions will be made over your head.

The first two years of the market development is too crazy, a lot of do membership system of the cinema have no voice in the end. The bottom line is that everyone agrees that online ticketing is a better model, one that theaters can't resist in the age of traffic. But now that the age of traffic is increasingly a thing of the past, it's hard to say whether it's time to build a longer term business ecosystem after the epidemic. But no matter do business or do product is also good, must stand in the medium and long-term dimension to see the pattern good or bad. Like good wine, it takes time to grow, it takes time to taste.

The same is true of investing, and I particularly agree with Zhang Lei, founder of hillhouse capital. The investment depends first on the person, and then on whether that person can create value over a longer period of time, and ultimately on a time-value product.

Over the past decade or so, the development of the cinema has been smooth, with no major setbacks. After this outbreak, theaters will change in two ways in a short period of time. First, recovery may take time and patience is needed. As an old saying goes, "illness comes in waves, illness goes out in waves. " Users are anxious, and cinemas can hardly make money without an atmosphere in which everyone can gather to spend. Even if the theater is open, the studio is not necessarily confident that the opening time may be delayed. Producers, producers and distributors alike are on the fence.

Second, now is a good time for cinema consolidation. China currently has more than 40 cinema lines, the cinema is also thousands of investment institutions, there are some regulatory agencies, the market is very chaotic. As for who will integrate, who has the capital, who has the vision, who can go to integrate.

In this room, I would like to speak for the theater manager. Of course it's hard for the studios, it's hard for the theater managers, they're caught in the middle, they're not free. They also want all the good movies to go online, and they want the system to move forward, and the problem is not that they brought it, or that the industry is too chaotic. 40 theaters, 70,000 screens, and all kinds of power. Over the past two decades, our society has focused too much on wealth, too much on the economy itself, and too little on the heart.

In addition to revolutionizing cinema,

It also gets the fans off the field

The film industry has certainly brought in a lot of good people over the years, many of whom have gone for career or investment opportunities. But an industry after big waves wash sand, will definitely keep the doer, let the pure lover leave the field.

After the outbreak, many investors will leave. Whether speculating or investing, it takes time to exit. The entertainment industry's exit timetable is not particularly clear. Especially in the past two years, a lot of radical psychological calm down, because of many force majeure, under the calculation of the loss of more and more projects.

The result of a natural disaster is often very systematic. It interrupts many chains. Once something goes wrong in the middle, it's not so easy to fix.

We recently launched a hiring round of about 100 people because we found that the animation chain may have some management risks down the road. For many production outsourcing companies, technology companies, if there is no project, they can not have income. Chinese startups don't have a lot of cash reserves for three months. An outbreak can make many companies'normal revenues uncertain, and that uncertainty can risk team stability or the abrupt dissolution of a good team.

It will hit founders and investors hard, it will drive impatient people away, but it is also a good time to invest on a scale. A few days ago, I was asked by my friends in the investment circle if it was a good time to invest in a movie theater. I said yes, of course, but also consider the market space, unless you can develop a new product model.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Image / visual China

The film market is too small, with $70 billion a year for screenings, $35 billion for cinemas and more than $25 billion for the studios. For China's tens of thousands of movie theaters, a total of more than 30 billion yuan, for many investors business is too small.

So investors should not only do the movie theater box office business, but should be the movie theater scene consumption. When you come out of a movie theater, you go from being an audience to being a user. It's especially important to figure out how to get the audience to consume the experience 10 minutes before and 10 minutes after entering the scene. I often go to Sanlitun to see movies, and the parking lot outside is the door, there is no post-screening consumption scene, for the film derivative scene, the planning is very unreasonable.

See Art film, I like to go to Beijing Broadway Film Center, go early, still can go to the bookstore to buy a book, finished, still can go for a cup of coffee. In fact, books may cost more than movie tickets. So investors don't need to look at the $30 billion plus revenue from the movie theater market, which could have an extension of $100 billion or more.

The same is true online, want to expand the market innovation, the current model of innovation is too weak, too conservative. Content itself has a strong trading value, and the consumer power it brings is not weak at all.

Companies often blame each other for not doing a good job of the content itself and not doing a good job of commercializing it. The content is done, and the content itself is commercially viable. There are many times when a thing is not done well, it is often given another reason for it. For example, when we make art films, many people will say, "you guys are really sentimental. " In fact, one of my least favorite words when I make movies is "sentimental. " I always think "feelings" is used to cover up the box office is not ideal or weak commercial capacity reputation fig leaf. What I choose to do is based solely on my personal interests, or my trust in the producer director, not my feelings, not my productivity.

The Future of art film

It's a line distribution and an art space

For the past year, I have refused all media interviews and have not participated in any public business activities. One is busy at work, and the other requires some deep thought. The time has come for a shift in China's entertainment market.

In the next phase, I'd like to position Sky City as a production company, not just a content company. Product companies need to reach an agreement with the audience from a world view and a value perspective. Companies need to move slowly forward in time, producing content that users like, rather than consuming it all at once. I hope that one day people will not be as enthusiastic about the box office and data as they are today, but will care more about the people who choose to pay for it. Whether or not they're excited and satisfied enough, whether or not they'll be immersed in your film, identify with your values, and share your work with others is a long term mechanism.

In the future, we will long-term efforts in content and user relations, really establish a "and users become friends" mechanism. Now, all of sky city's creative and design models are moving in that direction. We may not be a big company, but it must be a film company with texture.

I especially hope that there will be sub-line distribution, sub-focus distribution model out. Art Films should not be like commercial films. They should have their own operating space, be self-contained, and be able to support long-term screenings. Although now some of the art line also do well, but most are still a franchise, not many independent operations. There should be some capital out, to do the art line and film matching the art space. I especially like the long-term interaction between high-quality movies and their users. In addition, China should have some artistic film funds similar to those in France.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
This outbreak, for large shopping malls of consumer products have a great impact. If a shopping mall area or a floor out, do some film space, I believe it is no less than the drainage of the bookstore. Large shopping malls such public consumption scene, in the past cinema to help them solve the flow of people, to solve the top floor no one to go to the embarrassment. But art films have medium to long term effects, and I suggest that public spaces of all kinds, such as co working spaces, small industrial parks, and Secondary Industrial Zones, be transformed into more artistic spaces. Like 798, it's an art curatorial Mecca for many, though it's now limited by all kinds of commercialization. But a lot of people need a place where art is about telling the truth, and art is not virtual.

This outbreak has given us a sense of panic, a sense of unease. Insecurity, in fact, is the value of blind spots, psychological imbalance, it and personal wealth, education has nothing to do. The mass panic of a while ago made me think that we didn't deserve the material things we have today. I want our content to inherit something and expand something, not just create a dream for the audience. The content itself, especially the movie, is often a dream-making machine, but I hope that the movie we're making is more than just a dream, it opens people up, and it touches them differently.
